Recover corrupt .bashrc

# copy corrupted file
$ /bin/cp ~/.bashrc ~/copy-bashrc
# load the default copy
$ /bin/cp /etc/skel/.bashrc ~/
# activate changes
$ source .bashrc

Find public ip

$ dig TXT +shor o-o myaddr.l.google.com

Drive info

$ sudo cfdisk

Usb info

$ lsusb

Search for a running pid

# more verbose
$ ps -A | grep <app>

# returns pid
$ pgrep <app>

Process Tree

$ pstree

Graphic kill utuility

$ xkill

Find whats blocking port and kill

# find app
$ netstat -tulpn

# find pid
$ ps -A | grep <app>

# kill pid
$ kill <pid>

Create all necessary folders in filepath

$ mkdir -p

Remove all remnants of an install

$ sudo apt purge <app\>

Check disk usage

$ df -h    # list disk use percentage

$ df -h /dev/sda1    # for particular drive

$ df -H --output=source,size,used,avail    # cleaner output

$ du -h    # list directory and sub directory contents by size  

$ du -h -s *    # summary does not list sub directories

Hiding Login/Password as Environment Variables

  • cd ~
  • nano .bash_profile
  • export USER="jdoe"
  • export PASS="1234"
  • ctrl-x, y
  • source .bash_profile

CRONTAB

  • Flags(-l:list, -r:remove, -e:edit)
  • Use shell scripts(<scriptname.sh>
  • Include "shebang" (#!bin/bash) as first line of shell script
  • Export environment variables in shell script
  • Use absolute path(/home/user/path/to/*)
  • Use "." in place of "source" command for crontab
  • Use "MAILTO='foo@bar.net'" as first line in crontab to receive notification of every cronjob
  • Cron logs to /var/log/syslog
  • For cron specific logs(grep CRON /var/log/syslog)

  • lolcat
  • fortune | cowsay
  • sl

Snippets¶

Add Docker group

$ sudo groupadd docker

$ sudo usermod -aG docker $USER

$ newgrp docker

Docker run tags

-d detached
-it interactive/tty
-p manual define port
-P automatic define port
-v volume

Remove all containers and images

$ docker system prune -a

Remove volumes

$ docker volume prune

Remove Containers

$ sudo docker rm <container_id>

Remove Images

$ sudo docker image rm  <image_id>

Remember to add "." to the end of build commands to specify current directory

$ sudo docker build -t <project\> .

Use ENV (not CMD, RUN) to set environment variables in container

Play With Docker Tutorial

$ sudo docker run -dp 80:80 docker/getting-started:pwd

Exec as root

$ docker exec -u 0 -it <mycontainer\> <bash(ubuntu) or sh(alpine)\>

Start/Stop docker-compose

$ docker-compose up

$ docker-compose down

Stop and remove all running containers

$ docker rm $(docker stop $(docker ps -a -q))

Create a volume

$ docker volume create <name>

Named Volume

$ docker run -dp 3000:3000 -v todo-db:/etc/todos <tag>

Bind Mount

$ docker run -dp 3000:3000 -w /app -v $PWD:/app

Create Network

$ docker network create <name>

JENKINS¶

Getting Started with Jenkins

SchoolofDevops-learn-jenkins

Run Jenkins (Directory must contain jenkins.war file)

  • java -jar jenkins.war --httpPort=8080

Trigger Remote Build

  • http://<username>:<api-token>@localhost:8080/job/<job-name>/build?token=<authentication-token>

Create Jenkins Pipeline With Jenkinsfile

  • install pipeline plugin
  • fork and clone source code
  • cd to directory
  • create Jenkinsfile with $ nano Jenkinsfile
  • git add Jenkinsfile, commit and push origin master
  • create new item as pipeline, include repo link

List of available environment variables

http://localhost:8080/env-vars.html

Jenkinsfile¶

Scripted syntax seems to work better for me than declarative syntax

node {
    stage('SCM Checkout'){
        git 'git@github.com:jmrobinsonma/myflasksite.git'
    }
    stage('Building'){
        sh 'python3 -m venv venv'
        sh '. venv/bin/activate'
        sh 'pip3 install -r requirements.txt'
    }
    stage('Testing'){
        sh 'python3 test.py'
    }
    stage('Docker build'){
        sh 'docker build -t jmrobinson/myflasksite .'
    }
    stage('Push Docker image'){
        withCredentials([string(credentialsId: 'dockerpass', variable: 'DOCKERPWD')]) {
            sh "docker login -u jmrobinson -p ${DOCKERPWD}"
        }
        sh 'docker push jmrobinson/myflasksite'
    }
}

PARAMETERS

agent any
parameters {
    choice(name: 'VERSION', choices: ['1.1.0', '1.2.0', '1.3.0'], description: '')
    booleanParam(name: 'executeTests', defaultValue: true, description: '')
}

stages {
    stage() {
        when {
            expression {
                params.executeTests
            }
        }
        steps {
            echo "testing ${VERSION}"
        }
    }
}

CREDENTIALS

Global definition

agent any
    environment {
        SERVER_CREDENTIALS = credentials('dockerhub-creds')
    }
stages {
    stage {
        step {
            echo "deploy with ${SERVER_CREDENTIALS}"
        }
    }
}

For use in one stage

    steps {
    withCredentials([
        usernamePassword(credentials: 'docker-hub', usernameVariable: USER, passwordVariable: PASS)
    ]) {
        sh "deploy with ${USER} ${PASS}"
    }
}

BUILDOZER¶

Build a Mobile App- @realpython

Buildozer Dependencies

Setup

  • pip3 install buildozer
  • Then, create a new folder and navigate to it in your terminal. Once youre there, youll need to run the following command:
  • buildozer init

  • This will create a buildozer.spec file that youll use to configure your build. For this example, you can edit the first few lines of the spec file as follows: [app]

  • (str) Title of your application title = KvCalc

  • (str) Package name package.name = kvcalc

  • (str) Package domain (needed for android/ios packaging) package.domain = org.kvcalc

  • At this point, youre almost ready to build your application, but first, youll want to install the dependencies for buildozer. Once those are installed, copy your calculator application into your new folder and rename it to main.py. This is required by buildozer. If you dont have the file named correctly, then the build will fail.

  • buildozer -v android debug

FLASK¶

Basic Setup

  • Create python virtual environment (python3 -m venv <env_name>)
  • Activate virtual environment (source <env_name>/bin/activate)
  • Create a basic python script without html 
from flask import Flask
app = Flask(__name__)
@app.route('/')
def hello():
    return "Hello World!"
if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run()
  • Create a templates folder for .html files (mkdir templates)
  • Create a basic python script with html
from flask import Flask, render_template
app = Flask(__name__)
@app.route('/')
def home():
    return render_template('<name\>.html')
if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run()

Debug Mode

if __name__ == '__main__':
app.run(debug=True)

Basic UnitTest

import <project>
import unittest


class MyTestCase(unittest.TestCase):

def setUp(self):
    <project>.app.testing = True
    self.app = <project>.app.test_client()

def test_home(self):
    response = self.app.get('/')
    # Make your assertions
    self.assertEqual(response.status_code, 200)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    unittest.main()

DEPLOYING FLASK APP TO LINUX SERVER¶

Setup ssh in Remote Server

  • # ssh root@<ip_address>
  • # apt update && apt upgrade
  • # hostnamectl set-hostname <name>
  • # nano /etc/hosts (add ip and hostname)

/etc/hosts

127.0.0.1       localhost
<ip_address\>  <hostname\>
 The following lines are desirable for IPv6 capable hosts
::1     localhost ip6-localhost ip6-loopback
ff02::1 ip6-allnodes
ff02::2 ip6-allrouters
  • # adduser <username>
  • # adduser <username> sudo
  • # ssh <username>@
  • \$ mkdir ~/.ssh

Local Machine

  • \$ ssh-keygen -b 4096
  • \$ scp ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub <username>@<ip_address>:~/.ssh/authorized_keys

Remote Server

  • \$ sudo chmod 700 ~/.ssh/
  • \$ sudo chmod 600 ~/.ssh/*

Disable Root on Remote Server

  • \$ sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config (PasswordAuthentication=no, PermitRootLogin=no)
  • \$ sudo systemctl restart sshd

Firewall for Remote Server

  • \$ sudo apt install ufw
  • \$ sudo ufw default allow outgoing
  • \$ sudo ufw default deny incoming
  • \$ sudo ufw allow ssh
  • \$ sudo ufw allow 5000
  • \$ sudo ufw enable
  • \$ sudo ufw status

After Installing Nginx

  • \$ sudo ufw allow http/tcp
  • \$ sudo ufw delete allow 5000

Create requirements.txt on Local Machine

  • \$ pip3 freeze > requirements.txt
  • \$ scp -r ~/<project_folder> <username>@<ip_address>:~/

Configure App on Remote Server

  • \$ sudo apt install python3-pip
  • \$ sudo apt install python3-venv
  • \$ python3 -m venv <<project_folder>/<environment_name>>
  • \$ cd <project_folder>
  • \$ source <environment_name>/bin/activate
  • \$ pip install -r requirements.txt

Optional

To create a json file for environment variables

  • \$ sudo touch /etc/confg.json
  • \$ sudo nano config.py Update to access environment variables from config.json with .get() method

Run Flask with Default server

  • \$ export FLASK_APP=<project_name>.py
  • \$ flask run --host=0.0.0.0

Install Nginx and Gunicorn on Remote Server

  • \$ sudo apt install nginx
  • \$ pip install gunicorn
  • \$ sudo rm /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/default
  • \$ sudo nano /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/<project_name>

Nginx configuration <project_name>

server {
    listen 80;
    server_name <ip_address>;
    location /static {
         alias /home/<username>/<project_folder>/static;
    }
    location / {
        proxy_pass http://localhost:8000;
        include /etc/nginx/proxy_params;
        proxy_redirect off;
    }

}

Update Firewall

  • \$ sudo ufw allow http/tcp
  • \$ sudo ufw delete allow 5000

Restart Nginx

  • \$ sudo systemctl restart nginx

Install Supervisor

  • \$ sudo apt install supervisor
  • \$ sudo nano /etc/supervisor/conf.d/<project_name>.conf

<project_name>.conf

[program:jupyter_page]
directory=/home/jmrobinson/jupyterpage
command=/home/jmrobinson/jupyterpage/jupyter_env/bin/gunicorn -w 3 jupyter_page>
user=jmrobinson
autostart=true
autorestart=true
stopasgroup=true
killasgroup=true
stderr_logfile=/var/log/jupyterpage/jupyterpage.err.log
stdout_logfile=/var/log/jupyterpage/jupyterpage.out.log

Create Log Files

  • \$ sudo touch /var/log/<project_name>/<project_name>.err.log
  • \$ sudo touch /var/log/<project_name>/<project_name>.out.log
  • \$ sudo supervisorctl reload

Encrypt with LetsEncrypt/Certbot

  • \$ sudo apt update
  • \$ sudo apt install software-properties-common
  • \$ sudo add-apt-repository universe
  • \$ sudo add-apt-repository ppa:certbot/certbot
  • \$ sudo apt update
  • \$ sudo apt install python-certbot-nginx The nginx config file may be updated to show domain instead of ip
  • \$ sudo certbot --nginx

Allow Https Traffic Through Firewall

  • \$ sudo ufw allow https

System Restart Required

$ cat /var/run/reboot-required.pkgs

Check log

$ xargs apt-get changelog < /var/run/reboot-required.pkgs

Restart system

$ sudo systemctl reboot

SQLALCHEMY¶

Flask-Sqlalchemy select, insert, delete

Basic Template

from sqlalchemy import create_engine, Column, String
from sqlalchemy.ext.declarative import declarative_base
from sqlalchemy.orm import sessionmaker, relationship

Base = declarative_base()
class Posts(Base):

    __tablename__ = "base"

    timing = Column(String(120), unique=False, nullable=False,   primary_key=True)
    title_text = Column(String(120), unique=False, nullable=False)
    price = Column(String(120), unique=False, nullable=False)
    link = Column(String(120), unique=False, nullable=False)

engine = create_engine('sqlite:///search_results.db')  #echo=True for output to console
                             # ^^^ or ////home/user/path/to/folder
Base.metadata.create_all(bind=engine)            
Session = sessionmaker(bind=engine)
session = Session()

session.add(post)
session.commit()
session.close()

Catch IntegrityError

   from sqlalchemy import exc

   try:
       pass
   except exc.IntegrityError as e:
       session.rollback()

Local connection engine

import sqlalchemy as db

engine = db.create_engine('sqlite:////home/jrob/db_api/free-stuff.db')
connection = engine.connect()
metadata = db.MetaData()
posts = db.Table('posts', metadata, autoload=True, autoload_with=engine)

query = db.select([posts])
result_proxy = connection.execute(query)
results = result_proxy.fetchall()
last_five = results[-5:]
print(f"{len(results)} in /db_api/")

for i,r in enumerate(last_five[::-1]):
    print(f"\nResult {i+1}:\n{r}")
